SIMPLE: efface
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Efface
<hw>Ef*face"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Effaced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Effacing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>effacer</ets>; pref. <ets>es-</ets> (L. <ets>ex</ets>) +
<ets>face</ets> face; prop., to destroy the face or form. See
<er>Face</er>, and cf. <er>Deface</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause
to disappear (as anything impresses or inscribed upon a surface) by
rubbing out, striking out, etc.; to erase; to render illegible or
indiscernible; <as>as, to <ex>efface</ex> the letters on a monument, or
the inscription on a coin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy, as a mental impression; to wear
away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Efface</qex> from his mind the theories and notions vulgarly
received.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To blot out; expunge; erase; obliterate; cancel;
destroy. -- <er>Efface</er>, <er>Deface</er>. To <xex>deface</xex> is to
injure or impair a figure; to <xex>efface</xex> is to rub out or
destroy, so as to render invisible.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effaceable</ent>⟦br⟧
